##In the face of the impact of the epidemic, how to implement the first-stage Procurement Agreement between China and the United States?

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

In view of the reality of the impact of the epidemic, priority may be given to the implementation of relevant agreements such as medical supplies, and technical cooperation and personnel exchanges in the extended areas between the two sides can be promoted while guaranteeing the normal rights and interests of the Chinese side, to turn the outbreak into an opportunity for bilateral cooperation

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By Xu Qiyuan

At present, the epidemic has had an impact on China's macro-economic operation, during the Spring Festival, some service industries have been a greater impact. Against this backdrop, $200bn of procurement commitments in the first phase agreement signed on January 15th between the US and China could be affected.

If possible, China should, in an appropriate manner, propose to postpone the implementation of this procurement plan.

Four reasons will force China to delay purchases

China's import demand hit as economic growth slows.

China's domestic airlines have been hit hard, with a sharp drop in passenger traffic and flights. Airline operation condition will suffer bigger impact, capital chain also will be affected. At present, the development of the epidemic still has some uncertainty, it is difficult to implement a large-scale aircraft procurement program in the short term.

In addition, domestic industrial production has not yet fully restored to normal order, the overall production progress than in previous years lag significantly. In a more optimistic scenario, even if the country is almost back to production in early March, production will be delayed by one month, and it will take longer for the affected areas to resume production. As a result, China's demand for American imports of industrial machinery, electrical equipment and energy will also need to be significantly delayed in the first phase of the agreement.

China's balance of payments pressure will increase significantly in the first quarter, and increased procurement will further increase the pressure on the balance of payments imbalance.

Under the impact of the epidemic, although imports have declined, exports may face greater pressure. Even in some areas, the export manufacturing sector will face considerable pressure from supply chain disruptions, human flow barriers and isolation, the lack of protective materials for production and the possible loss of orders as a result of significant delays in the resumption of work.

As a reference, the SARS period saw a trade deficit of US $1.02 billion in the first quarter of 2003, the second quarterly deficit since 1994. For comparison, the trade surplus in the first quarter of 2002 was $7.27 billion. For now, China's trade surplus could fall sharply in the first quarter of this year, or even turn into a deficit.

US measures such as a public health emergency, flight bans and visa suspension will also reduce China's access to US imports of goods and services.

China's services imports in 2019 should be $12.8 billion higher than in 2017, according to the first phase of the agreement. In the area of trade in services, the most important is tourism. Chinese tourists to the US peaked in 2017, then fell 5.7 per cent year-on-year in the full year of 2018 and 4.7 per cent in the first three quarters of 2019 amid trade conflicts, according to the US National Tourism Office (NTTO) .

The outbreak will further reduce the number of Chinese tourists visiting the United States in 2020 from 2019. In early February 2020, Delta Airlines, United Airlines and American Airlines suspended all U.S. flights to and from mainland China until late March or late April. This will affect business travel and tourism to the United States for Chinese tourists, thus reducing the service imports to the United States that I promised in the first phase of the agreement. Assuming no change in per capita spending, Chinese travel to the United States in 2020 would be 21.4 percent lower than in 2017 under trade in services, which would reduce China's purchases of travel services from the United States by $7.55 billion. At the same time, will also affect the insurance and other related financial services. It is clear that this will make it much harder for China to meet its procurement commitments in the services sector, and that the new constraints come mainly from US restrictions.

In addition, the suspension of passenger flights will also affect the passenger aircraft abdomen transport intermodal services, thus reducing China's imports of high value-added products from the United States. Of course, passenger aircraft belly transport accounts for relatively small, so the impact is not big, but if cargo aviation and shipping affected, China will be difficult to normally implement import commitments.

On the supply side, the delay in China's resumption of work has had an impact on global supply chains and could have an impact on the ability of US companies to deliver goods for export.

Wuhan is one of the four largest passenger car bases in China, with half of the top 20 auto parts in the world. In addition, the scope of the delay to resume work far beyond Wuhan, involving a wider range of industries. Domestic manufacturing supply chains have been hit.

Germany's Bosch Group has warned that its global supply chain could be disrupted if the outbreak lasts longer. In fact, Hyundai has suspended production of an important model and plans to phase out its entire vehicle line. Nissan will also stop part of its production line. In the US, about 15 per cent of the auto industry is dependent on Chinese suppliers for parts, and 50 per cent or more for electronics such as smartphones and laptops.

It is possible to postpone purchases from the US

The first phase of the agreement also sets out the applicable terms of the outbreak. The agreement states that, "If one party is delayed in fulfilling its obligations under this agreement due to natural disasters or other unforeseen circumstances beyond the control of both parties, both parties shall hold consultations. " Given the overwhelming impact of the epidemic on the Chinese economy, the United States has also initiated a public health emergency and acknowledged the seriousness and uncontrollability of the impact, so that both sides can explore the possibility of postponing the implementation of the first-phase agreement.

The U. S. Government and public opinion have been prepared for the possibility that the outbreak could lead to a delay in the implementation of the Phase I agreement. Comments in the New York Times, Forbes and others have pointed to this possibility. February 4th, lary Kudlow, chief economic adviser to US President Donald Trump, said in an interview with Fox business news that "it may take longer to achieve export growth in the first phase of the agreement due to the outbreak in China. ".

The outbreak should be turned into an opportunity for cooperation

To avoid the outbreak of the disease to escalate bilateral tensions, the outbreak of the disease into an opportunity for cooperation. The delay in implementing the first phase of the agreement, and the slower than expected pace of Chinese imports, could increase public pressure on the Donald Trump administration in the United States, inflame tensions in bilateral relations and make the second phase of negotiations more difficult for both sides. To this end, we can give priority to the implementation of relevant agreements, such as medical supplies, based on the reality of the impact of the epidemic, and promote technical cooperation and personnel exchanges between the two sides in the areas of extension, while guaranteeing our normal rights and interests, we will turn the outbreak into an opportunity for bilateral cooperation and actively expand areas of bilateral cooperation.

Xu Qiyuan is a research fellow at the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences and Director of research at CF40; editor Wang Yanchun
